#v(0.8em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*The idea.* Every one of the 620 one-sided 7-cell polyhexes (rotations identified, reflections distinct) can be placed, under some rotation and translation, somewhere inside the teal region above. The bounding box of the container is 8 x 5, fitting inside the $(n+1) times (n+1)$ search rectangle $=8 times 8$.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*Piece count.* The one-sided polyhex count (OEIS A006535) is $1, 1, 3, 10, 33, 147, 620$ for $n = 1$ through $7$. At $n = 7$, the container holds 620 distinct shapes in just 21 cells by overlap -- most piece placements share cells with other placements.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*How it was proved.* For each $n = 1, ..., 7$, a SAT solver (cadical) with CEGAR connectivity search descended $k -> k - 1$ within the $(n+1) times (n+1)$ axial rectangle until producing a model of size $a(n)$ and an UNSAT certificate at $a(n) - 1$. Each value is cross-checked by an independent pure-Python geometric verifier (disjoint code path from the solver) AND a machine-verified DRAT or LRAT proof (drat-trim for $n = 1..6$, cadical-`--lrat` + lrat-check for $n = 7$). All three stacks agree on $n = 1..7$.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*Sequence so far.* $a(1..7) = 1, 2, 4, 7, 11, 15, 21$. No closed-form or small-coefficient recurrence matches all seven values; the observed growth is polynomial of order 2 with $n^2 \/ 3 <= a(n) <= 5n^2 \/ 8$ empirically for $n <= 7$ (UNVERIFIED as a general bound).
]